==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harm
<hw>Harm</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧rm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>harm</ets>, <ets>hearm</ets>, AS. <ets>hearm</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>harm</ets>, G. <ets>harm</ets> grief, Icel. <ets>harmr</ets>, Dan.
<ets>harme</ets>, Sw. <ets>harm</ets>; cf. OSlav. & Russ.
<ets>sram'</ets> shame, Skr. <ets>⟦cced⟧rama</ets> toil, fatigue.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Injury; hurt; damage; detriment; misfortune.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which causes injury, damage, or loss.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We, ignorant of ourselves,⟦br⟧
Beg often our own <qex>harms</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Mischief; evil; loss; injury. See
<er>Mischief</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harm</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Harm
<hw>Harm</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Harmed</conjf> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧rmd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Harming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>harmen</ets>, AS.
<ets>hearmian</ets>. See <er>Harm</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To
hurt; to injure; to damage; to wrong.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though yet he never <qex>harmed</qex> me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No ground of enmity between us known⟦br⟧
Why he should mean me ill or seek to <qex>harm</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harmaline</ent>⟦br⟧
